That gap is the source of a lot of bad budget decisions.

Australia's digital ad market hit $18.4 billion in 2025, up 11.5% year on year ([IAB Australia/PwC, 2026](https://iabaustralia.com.au/news/internet-advertising-spend-increases-11-5-to-reach-18-4-billion-in-2025/)). Globally, only 39% of buy-side users employ attribution, MMM, and incrementality testing together ([IAB State of Data 2026](https://www.iab.com/insights/2026-state-of-data-report/)). The majority rely on a single method, usually the numbers each ad platform reports about itself.

A peer-reviewed [IEEE paper from Dropbox's data science team](https://doi.org/10.1109/ACCESS.2026.3670337) and Avinash Kaushik's [Modern Analytics Maturity Model (MAMM)](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/akaushik_most-analytics-teams-suffer-in-silence-share-7442951376919224320) both landed in March 2026 with the same conclusion: marketing measurement sits on a maturity ladder, and most companies are far lower than they think. Kaushik's MAMM frames analytics organisations across 6 levels and 10 dimensions. The map below zooms in: can you trust the numbers you're using to allocate budget?

